    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the SINGLE `sys_ui_policy`
    row that enforces conditional polymorphic field rendering on the
    `x_casemgmt_case_party` custom table inside the scoped application
    `x_casemgmt`.

    This file produces THE SINGLE UI Policy record in the entire scoped
    application per AAP Section 0.4.1 (Refactored Structure Planning) and
    AAP Section 0.4.3 (Polymorphic association via single-table choice +
    UI Policy). The agent prompt's Phase 9 Insight 1 confirms exactly
    one record total in this XML file.

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.4.3):
      Implement the ServiceNow-native equivalent of ArkCase's JPA
      single-table inheritance pattern from PersonAssociation.java, which
      uses:
          @Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.SINGLE_TABLE)
          @DiscriminatorColumn(name = "cm_class_name",
                               discriminatorType = DiscriminatorType.STRING)
          @DiscriminatorValue("com.armedia.acm.plugins.person.model.PersonAssociation")
      collapsed into a single ServiceNow table `x_casemgmt_case_party`
      with a `party_type` Choice field that conditionally shows/hides
      and conditionally requires the `person` (Reference -> sys_user)
      and `organization` (Reference -> core_company) reference fields.

    BEHAVIOR MATRIX (the imperative onCondition script enforces this for
    all three party_type states):

        Case 1: party_type == "Person"
            person field        : visible = true,  mandatory = true
            organization field  : visible = false, mandatory = false

        Case 2: party_type == "Organization"
            person field        : visible = false, mandatory = false
            organization field  : visible = true,  mandatory = true

        Case 3: party_type == "" (empty, new record)
            person field        : visible = false, mandatory = false
            organization field  : visible = false, mandatory = false

    The "empty" case (new record before user picks party_type) keeps
    BOTH reference fields hidden and not mandatory. The user picks
    party_type first (which is itself mandatory at the dictionary level
    per ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_party_party_type.xml), and only
    then does the appropriate reference field appear. Per the agent
    prompt's Phase 9 Insight 2, the empty branch has DISTINCT semantics
    that differ from any populated value - it must not be consolidated
    with another branch.

    ARCHITECTURE DECISION (agent prompt's REVISED ARCHITECTURE):
      The agent prompt initially considered two competing approaches:

        Option A (declarative): TWO `sys_ui_policy` records each with
          TWO `sys_ui_policy_action` children, both with
          reverse_if_false=true. The agent prompt's analysis found an
          unavoidable order-conflict in the empty-state case: when
          neither policy's forward condition is true, both policies
          reverse simultaneously, and within a single load cycle their
          conflicting reversed states for the same field must be
          tie-broken by the `order` field. Last-writer-wins semantics
          produce the WRONG empty-case result (one of the reference
          fields appears as visible+mandatory instead of hidden) per
          the agent prompt's Phase 4 analysis.

        Option B (imperative): ONE `sys_ui_policy` record with
          run_scripts=true and a script_true block that imperatively
          handles all three branches deterministically.

      The agent prompt's Phase 9 Insight 1 selects Option B as the
      ONLY way to cleanly handle all three states without ordering
      ambiguity. This file therefore contains EXACTLY ONE record:
      a single `sys_ui_policy` with the script_true entry point.

    REQUIRED FIELDS HANDLED IMPERATIVELY (NOT at dictionary level):
      Per the parent dictionary entries
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_party_person.xml
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_party_organization.xml
      the dictionary-level `<mandatory>false</mandatory>` is INTENTIONAL.
      The conditional mandatory state is enforced HERE in the UI Policy
      via g_form.setMandatory(...) at form runtime. This is the canonical
      ServiceNow pattern for polymorphic mandatory: the dictionary
      declares the column as nullable, and the UI Policy enforces
      conditional required-ness based on the discriminator value. This
      design is documented in those dictionary entries' `<comments>`
      element.

    SOURCE-SIDE SEMANTIC REFERENCE (read-only context, NOT byte-for-byte
