          @JoinColumn(name = "cm_person_id", nullable = false)
          private Person person;
          @ManyToOne(cascade = { ... }, optional = false)
          @JoinColumn(name = "cm_organization_id", nullable = false)
          private Organization organization;

      ArkCase's polymorphism uses two separate JPA entities living in
      two separate physical tables (`acm_person_assoc` and
      `acm_person_org_assoc`), each with its own mandatory @ManyToOne
      reference. The discriminator column stores the Java fully-qualified
      class name - opaque to non-Java consumers, fragile under refactors.

      The ServiceNow target FIXES this by collapsing both ArkCase
      tables into ONE table (x_casemgmt_case_party) with:
        - A user-friendly `party_type` Choice field with values
          "Person" and "Organization" (per
          ../choices/sys_choice_case_party_party_type.xml) replacing
          the JVM class-name discriminator
        - A `person` reference field (Reference -> sys_user) replacing
          the @ManyToOne Person reference
        - An `organization` reference field (Reference -> core_company)
          replacing the @ManyToOne Organization reference
        - A `role_label` String(100) field replacing the legacy
          `personType`/`personToOrganizationAssociationType` Strings

      THIS UI POLICY is the ONLY mechanism that enforces the polymorphism
      at the form layer. Without it, the form would always show BOTH
      `person` and `organization` reference fields, which would confuse
      users and allow inconsistent records (e.g., a row with
      party_type=Person but `organization` populated). The UI Policy
      is therefore THE structural integrity guard for the polymorphic
      design at the UX layer.

    ENTRY-POINT FUNCTION CONTRACT:
      The script_true block contains a single function named
      `onCondition()`. ServiceNow's UI Policy framework looks for this
      EXACT function name as the entry point when run_scripts=true.
      The function takes NO arguments and returns nothing. It uses the
      globally-available `g_form` object (provided by ServiceNow's
      GlideForm runtime) to query the current value of `party_type`
      and to mutate the visibility and mandatory state of the
      `person` and `organization` fields. The function executes
      client-side in the user's browser - NEVER server-side.

    CRITICAL SCRIPT PROHIBITIONS (agent prompt's Phase 5 CRITICAL
    Script Rules):
      - NO g_form.clearValue('person') or g_form.clearValue('organization'):
        clearing on toggle would destroy user data on accidental
        party_type changes. The UI Policy preserves the underlying
        value; only visibility and mandatory flags change.
      - NO gs.eventQueue or any server-side calls: UI Policy scripts
        are client-side only.
      - NO console.log, alert(), or any developer-debug output:
        production UI Policy scripts are silent.
      - NO g_form.submit() or g_form.save(): UI Policy scripts adjust
        UI state, never persist.
      - NO == (loose equality): the strict-equality === avoids
        type-coercion bugs (e.g., if g_form.getValue ever returned 0
        or false in some edge case).
      - NO g_form.setVisible: deprecated/non-canonical in modern
        ServiceNow. Use g_form.setDisplay.

